The phrase "per-operation mutex" is doing a lot of work here, and it's almost certainly where the bug lives. There are a few distinct failure modes, and I'll rank them by how often I've seen each one cause exactly this symptom.

## Most likely: the mutex isn't shared

"Per-operation" often means each call to the function creates its own mutex instance. Every concurrent caller acquires a *different* lock, so there's zero actual mutual exclusion:

```
// BROKEN — each call gets its own lock
async function transferFunds(accountId, amount) {
  const mutex = new Mutex();        // ← fresh lock every time
  await mutex.acquire();
  const balance = await db.read(accountId);
  if (balance >= amount) {
    await db.write(accountId, balance - amount);
  }
  mutex.release();
}
```

The fix: the mutex must be **per-resource**, not per-operation. You want one lock per `accountId` (or whatever the contended entity is), and that lock must be shared across all callers:

```
// FIXED — one lock per logical resource, shared across callers
const locks = new Map();  // accountId → Mutex

function getLock(accountId) {
  if (!locks.has(accountId)) locks.set(accountId, new Mutex());
  return locks.get(accountId);
}

async function transferFunds(accountId, amount) {
  const mutex = getLock(accountId);
  await mutex.acquire();
  try {
    const balance = await db.read(accountId);
    if (balance >= amount) {
      await db.write(accountId, balance - amount);
    }
  } finally {
    mutex.release();
  }
}
```

## Second most likely: multiple process instances

Even if the mutex is correctly shared within a process, a process-local lock is invisible to other replicas. If you're running 3 pods / workers / instances, you have 3 independent locks — same bug, different scale.

Fixes, in order of preference:

1. **Database-level optimistic concurrency** — add a version column, `UPDATE ... WHERE version = @expected_version`, retry on conflict. This is almost always the right answer because it works regardless of topology. It's also the only approach that's correct if your DB could failover mid-transaction.

2. **`SELECT ... FOR UPDATE`** — pushes the lock into the database. Works well for single-database architectures but ties you to pessimistic row locking.

3. **Distributed lock** (Redis/Redlock, etcd, ZooKeeper) — if you truly need cross-process mutual exclusion beyond what the DB gives you. More operational complexity than most people realize; Redlock in particular has well-documented edge cases (Martin Kleppmann's analysis is worth reading).

## Third: async interleaving

In async runtimes (Node.js, Dart, Python asyncio), if your "mutex" is just a boolean flag and not an async-aware lock, an `await` between check and write yields control. Another coroutine runs, passes the same check, and you get duplicate writes — even in a single-threaded runtime.

---

## What I'd actually recommend

Skip the application-level mutex entirely and use **optimistic concurrency control** at the database:

```sql
-- Add: version INTEGER DEFAULT 0

-- Read
SELECT balance, version FROM accounts WHERE id = @id;

-- Write (only succeeds if nobody else wrote since our read)
UPDATE accounts
SET balance = @new_balance, version = version + 1
WHERE id = @id AND version = @read_version;

-- If affected_rows == 0 → conflict, retry the whole operation
```

This is correct across replicas, survives process crashes, doesn't require lock cleanup, and makes the concurrency invariant *visible in the schema* rather than implicit in application code. The retry loop is simple and the conflict rate under normal load is low.

The mutex approach has a seductive simplicity — "just lock before the critical section" — but it's solving a distributed coordination problem with a local primitive. The database is already a coordination point; lean on it.

Since we're in a Dart project, let's keep it in the family:

```dart
/// Validates an email address against RFC 5322 (simplified).
///
/// This hits the sweet spot between "regex from hell" and "just check for @".
/// It catches the things real users actually get wrong — missing domain,
/// double dots, spaces — without pretending to parse nested comments
/// that no mail server has seen since 1993.
bool isValidEmail(String email) {
  // One regex to rule them all? No. But one regex to catch 99.9% of real
  // addresses while rejecting obvious garbage? Yes.
  //
  // What this allows:
  //   - Standard: nick@example.com
  //   - Subaddressing: nick+tag@example.com
  //   - Dots in local part: first.last@example.com
  //   - Hyphens in domain: mail@my-company.co.uk
  //
  // What this rejects:
  //   - Missing local/domain: @example.com, nick@
  //   - Consecutive dots: nick..name@example.com
  //   - Spaces: nick @example.com
  //   - Missing TLD: nick@localhost (intentional — controversial but pragmatic)

  final pattern = RegExp(
    r"^[a-zA-Z0-9.!#$%&'*+/=?^_`{|}~-]+"  // local part (RFC 5322 dot-atom)
    r'@'
    r'[a-zA-Z0-9]'                           // domain starts alphanumeric
    r'(?:[a-zA-Z0-9-]{0,61}[a-zA-Z0-9])?'   // rest of first label
    r'(?:\.[a-zA-Z0-9](?:[a-zA-Z0-9-]{0,61}[a-zA-Z0-9])?)*' // more labels
    r'\.[a-zA-Z]{2,}$',                      // TLD: at least 2 chars
  );

  if (email.length > 254) return false; // RFC 5321 path length limit
  if (email.contains('..')) return false; // no consecutive dots

  final atIndex = email.indexOf('@');
  if (atIndex > 64) return false; // local part max 64 chars

  return pattern.hasMatch(email);
}
```

The interesting design decision here: **where to draw the line between permissive and strict**.

The RFC technically allows quoted strings (`"nick name"@example.com`), IP literals (`nick@[192.168.1.1]`), and all sorts of exotic forms. But in practice, if someone enters one of those, they've almost certainly made a typo. So this validates against *emails people actually use*, not emails the spec technically permits.

The `email.contains('..')` check is separate from the regex on purpose — it's clearer to read than encoding "no consecutive dots" into the pattern, and it's one of the most common typos.

If you want to actually test deliverability, of course, the only real answer is "send a confirmation email." But as a front-line input validator, this covers the ground well.
